answers.body_markdown:
In `list.rest = list;` you are setting the list.rest property back as a reference to itself which is why it says &quot;Circular&quot;. This is because in Javascript, [Objects and Arrays are passed by reference](https://medium.com/nodesimplified/javascript-pass-by-value-and-pass-by-reference-in-javascript-fcf10305aa9c). 

What you want to do is create a deep-copy of the original element. You can do that a few ways:

`JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(list))` will deconstruct to and from JSON (preserving all keys and all object depth). Alternatively `Object.assign({}, list)` will assign all of the object&#39;s 1st level keys to the new object. This means an object like this:
```json
{
   root: {
      inner: &quot;test&quot;,
   }
}
```
Will only be assigned the `root` key, but the `inner` will not get copied when doing `Object.assign`

Thus a solution for you would be:
```js
for (let i = array.length - 1; i &gt;= 0; i--) {
        list.rest = Object.assign({}, list);
        list.value = array[i];
    }
```
or 
```js
for (let i = array.length - 1; i &gt;= 0; i--) {
        list.rest = JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(list));
        list.value = array[i];
    }
```

